        Oh my gosh, a fellow Uncharted fan! HELLO! — I feel like I already like you. Do you remember the episode where Captain Vex had to navigate that whole diplomatic situation with the crystalline beings and she kept accidentally insulting them by making eye contact? That's basically my LIFE now. — Except with plants. And less crystal.

        Okay okay okay — must-see things. Let me think. I'm basically making a travel guide for my own accidental home, which is WILD.

        ¶

        First: the facility. I know that sounds boring - "come see the bureaucracy!" - but honestly? It's kind of amazing. There's this whole complex where the plants have set up administration and research and it's just... it's so EARNEST. Like, they have forms. For everything. And the forms have forms. And everyone is so serious about it and it's somehow the most charming thing ever? — Plus that's where I live, so if you visit the facility you can say hi!

        Second: the bioluminescent areas. There are parts of the forest where everything GLOWS at night. And I don't mean like, a little twinkle. I mean full-on "is this a dream sequence?" levels of glow. Blues and greens and sometimes these pulses of purple that move through the canopy like... like the forest is breathing light. I cried the first time I saw it. — Don't tell anyone. Actually, tell everyone, it's THAT beautiful.

        Third: if you can make it out to the hills, there's this ancient grove at the top. The trees there are OLD. Like, "witnessed the rise and fall of civilizations" old. And they're still growing, still reaching. Standing there makes you feel very small but in a good way? — In a "the universe is vast and ancient and I'm part of it" way.

        ¶

        Now. GIFTS. — I love that you're worried about this. "Who do I give it to, it's a whole planet!" — that made me laugh out loud. Okay so here's the thing: you're not giving a gift to the planet. You're giving a gift to whoever hosts you. And someone WILL host you, because that's how it works here. The bureaucracy will assign you a guide (they love assigning things) and that guide becomes kind of responsible for you. Bring something for them!

        What to bring: something shareable is good. Food travels well emotionally - like, the concept of "I brought you something to eat" translates really well across species. Seeds are VERY appreciated, especially if they're from somewhere the plants here haven't seen. Or honestly? Just bring something from home that you can explain. They love hearing about human stuff. A book, a photo, a weird snack. The gift is really just an excuse to tell a story.
      </text>
